{
  "text": "In some cases, clinical infections with C. albicans persist even when azole drugs are used at concentrations well above the minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) [CITATION_1] . In these examples, cell subpopulations continue to grow above their MIC in a phenomenon known as tolerance or heteroresistance [CITATION_2] . Robust production of b-glucan and extracellular DNA during biofilm formation promotes tolerance to multiple antifungal agents in C. albicans [CITATION_3] . Defects in intrinsic cellular function such as the calcineurin pathway, Hsp90, and membrane trafficking through endosomes can also contribute to azole tolerance [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Mutations leading to elevated azole tolerance may commonly precede progression to full drug resistance [CITATION_7] .",
